          "body": "David's response is four Hebrew words — 'I have sinned against the LORD.' There is no qualification, no mitigation, no deflection to Bathsheba's role or Joab's execution of the plan. The sin is owned vertically — against the LORD specifically, which Psalm 51:4 ('Against You, You only, I have sinned') makes explicit in David's own words about this same event. Nathan's response is immediate: 'The LORD has taken away your sin; you shall not die' (12:13). The speed of the forgiveness is as important as the forgiveness itself. There is no purgatorial waiting period, no probationary season of proving repentance. Confession meets immediate absolution. This models what the New Testament will name as the logic of 1 John 1:9 — the God who is faithful and righteous to forgive. But the 'nevertheless' of 12:14 is not a retraction. The child will die, not because David's guilt remains, but because the sin has given occasion to the enemies of the LORD to blaspheme (12:14). The temporal consequence is distinct from the guilt-consequence. Both must be held simultaneously."
