          "title": "The Rabbah coda — duty deferred, now done (12:26-31)",
          "body": "The chapter closes with the completion of the Ammonite war. Joab, who had been fighting Rabbah while David committed adultery and arranged murder (11:1, 14-17), has now captured the water supply and summons David to take the final prize, warning him that if he does not come, the city will be named after Joab instead (12:28). David comes, leads the final assault, takes the city, places the Ammonite crown on his own head, and returns to Jerusalem (12:29-31). The closing coda is not a military appendix awkwardly tacked on. It closes the frame opened in 11:1 — 'when kings go out to battle, David sent Joab.' The king who should have been at war is now finally at war. The duty he abandoned, creating the vacuum that his sin filled, is now belatedly executed. The crown sits on the head Nathan rebuked. The chapter thus ends with David restored to function — worshipping, comforting, leading — but carrying both the covenant love God has shown and the covenant curse God has declared. The sword is coming. The beloved child has been born. Both are true at once, and only the God who is light with no darkness at all can hold them together."
