        "number": 3,
        "title": "Confession and absolution — the grammar of immediate forgiveness",
        "range": "12:13",
        "excerpt": "Then David said to Nathan, \"I have sinned against the LORD.\" And Nathan said to David, \"The LORD also has taken away your sin; you shall not die.\"",
        "body": "Verse 13 is the chapter's soteriological center, and it occupies exactly one verse. Both David's confession and Nathan's absolution are grammatically complete in a single exchange, with no narrative gap between them. This compression is theologically crucial. The author of Samuel is not rushing past an awkward moment; he is showing what genuine confession and genuine grace look like when they meet each other.\n\nDavid's confession — 'I have sinned against the LORD' (*chata'ti lYHWH*) — is four Hebrew words. There is no indirect object naming another victim (no 'I have wronged Uriah' or 'I have wronged Bathsheba'), though those wrongs are real. The confession is vertical — *against the LORD* — because ultimately all sin is a violation of God's person and character, regardless of the human victim. Psalm 51 (which the superscript explicitly ties to this event) fills in what the narrative compresses: 'Against You, You only, I have sinned' (Ps 51:4). This is not denial of the horizontal damage; it is recognition that the horizontal damage is grounded in a vertical offense.\n\nNathan's absolution is equally direct: 'The LORD has taken away (*he'evir*) your sin; you shall not die.' The verb *he'evir* (from *avar*, to pass over, to cause to cross over) means to cause something to pass away from one place to another. It is used in the Day of Atonement language of Leviticus (cf. the scapegoat bearing away the iniquity of Israel, Lev 16:22). Nathan does not say God will forgive David eventually, or that David must prove his repentance through good works. He says the sin has been caused to pass away. The Puritan John Owen identified this as the pattern of imputed righteousness operating in the Old Testament — the guilt of sin transferred away from the sinner not because the sinner earned it but because God sovereignly provides a covering. The full Christological ground of that covering will not be visible until the cross, but the structure is already here.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chata* (I have sinned) is the qal perfect — a completed, owned act. *He'evir* (has taken away) is the hiphil — causative, God as the active agent of the removal. The sinner does not remove his own sin; God causes it to cross over."
